  "text": "## Node.js Child Process Command Injection Prevention\n\nNode.js implements comprehensive command injection prevention across its child_process module through JavaScript-level validation and C++ security checks.\n\n### JavaScript Entry Points and Validation\n\n**lib/child_process.js** contains the main public API:\n- **spawn(file, args, options)** (line 745) - Primary function for spawning processes\n- **fork(modulePath, args, options)** (line 122) - Spawns a Node.js process specifically for forking\n- **exec(command, options, callback)** (line 231) - Spawns a shell executing the given command\n- **execFile(file, args, options, callback)** (line 323) - Spawns a specific file/executable\n- **execFileSync(file, args, options)** (line 907) - Synchronous version of execFile\n- **execSync(command, options)** (line 945) - Synchronous version of exec\n- **spawnSync(file, args, options)** (line 823) - Synchronous version of spawn\n\n### Core Security Function: Null Byte Validation\n\n**validateArgumentNullCheck(arg, propName)** (line 963-967 in lib/child_process.js) implements the critical null byte validation:\n```javascript\nfunction validateArgumentNullCheck(arg, propName) {\n  if (typeof arg === 'string' && StringPrototypeIncludes(arg, '\\u0000')) {\n    throw new ERR_INVALID_ARG_VALUE(propName, arg, 'must be a string without null bytes');\n  }\n}\n```\nThis function prevents null byte injection attacks by rejecting any string arguments containing the null character (\\u0000), which could otherwise be used for command injection.\n\n**validateArgumentsNullCheck(args, propName)** (line 970-974) iterates over argument arrays and validates each element for null bytes, protecting against array-based injection attempts.\n\n### Argument Normalization with Validation\n\n**normalizeSpawnArguments(file, args, options)** (line 538-709) normalizes all spawn arguments:\n- Validates the file path for null bytes (line 540)\n- Validates all argument strings for null bytes (line 556: validateArgumentsNullCheck(args, 'args'))\n- Validates argv0 parameter for null bytes (line 597)\n- Validates shell parameter if provided (line 613)\n- Validates all environment variables for null bytes in keys and values (lines 691-692)\n\n**normalizeExecArgs(command, options, callback)** (line 188-206) normalizes exec command arguments:\n- Validates the command string for null bytes (line 190)\n- Sets shell mode to true by default for exec, preventing direct execution\n\n**normalizeExecFileArgs(file, args, options, callback)** (line 262-296) normalizes execFile arguments:\n- Validates argv0 parameter for null bytes (line 292)\n\n### Internal ChildProcess Class\n\n**lib/internal/child_process.js** contains the internal ChildProcess implementation:\n- **ChildProcess()** constructor (line 254-311) creates the native process wrapper using `this._handle = new Process()` which is the JavaScript wrapper for ProcessWrap\n- **ChildProcess.prototype.spawn(options)** (line 354-479) is the method that orchestrates the actual process spawning by calling `this._handle.spawn(options)` to invoke the C++ ProcessWrap\n- **ChildProcess.prototype.kill(sig)** (line 492-517) terminates the process\n- **setupChannel(target, channel, serializationMode)** (line 582-600) establishes IPC communication channels for fork operations\n\n### Native C++ ProcessWrap Binding\n\n**src/process_wrap.cc** provides the native binding to libuv process operations:\n\n**ProcessWrap class** (line 51) extends HandleWrap and represents the native handle for spawned processes.\n\n**ProcessWrap::Initialize()** (line 53-69) registers the native binding:\n- Sets up the Process constructor\n- Registers spawn and kill methods\n\n**ProcessWrap::Spawn()** (line 153-310) is the core native spawn function that:\n1. Extracts the spawn options from JavaScript (line 162-163)\n2. Validates permission via THROW_IF_INSUFFICIENT_PERMISSIONS macro (line 158-159)\n3. **Checks for Windows batch file** (line 204): Performs IsWindowsBatchFile() validation - a critical security check that prevents spawning batch files on Windows, which could be exploited for command injection\n4. Processes the file parameter (line 192-197)\n5. Processes and validates arguments array (line 208-225)\n6. Processes environment variables (line 237-250)\n7. Parses stdio configuration (line 253-254)\n8. Calls uv_spawn() to perform the actual system-level process spawn (line 286)\n\n**ProcessWrap::Kill()** (line 312-325) terminates a spawned process using uv_process_kill().\n\n**ProcessWrap::OnExit()** (line 327-343) is the callback handler invoked when a spawned process exits.\n\n**ProcessWrap::ParseStdioOptions()** (line 110-151) securely configures stdio handles for the spawned process.\n\n### Windows Security Check\n\n**src/util-inl.h** contains **IsWindowsBatchFile()** (line 541-543) which prevents execution of batch files on Windows. This is an additional injection prevention measure that blocks a common Windows-specific attack vector.\n\nThe same check is also performed in **src/spawn_sync.cc** (line 773) for synchronous spawning: `if (IsWindowsBatchFile(uv_process_options_.file)) return Just<int>(UV_EINVAL);`\n\n### Permission System\n\n**src/permission/child_process_permission.h** defines the **ChildProcessPermission** class (line 13) which implements permission checks for child process operations, allowing Node.js to be run with restricted permissions that can disable child process spawning entirely.\n\n### Security Chain Summary\n\nThe security model follows this call chain:\n1. User calls public API (spawn, exec, fork, etc.) in **lib/child_process.js**\n2. Arguments are normalized via **normalizeSpawnArguments** which calls **validateArgumentNullCheck** and **validateArgumentsNullCheck**\n3. All command strings, arguments, and environment variables are checked for null bytes\n4. A **ChildProcess** instance is created (lib/internal/child_process.js)\n5. **ChildProcess.prototype.spawn()** calls the native **ProcessWrap::Spawn()** method\n6. In C++, **ProcessWrap::Spawn()** checks for Windows batch files via **IsWindowsBatchFile()**\n7. Permission checks are enforced via the permission system\n8. The process is spawned via libuv's uv_spawn() call\n\nThis multi-layered approach prevents command injection through null bytes, Windows batch file exploitation, and enforces explicit permission checks before any child process can be spawned."
